<!-- Choosing the Right Method -->
<h2>How to Choose the Right Enforcement Method</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Assess the defendant's situation</strong><br>
    Do they have a job? Property? Bank accounts? Assets? Start with an Order to Obtain Information if you're unsure.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Consider the debt amount</strong><br>
    For smaller debts (under £1,000), Attachment of Earnings or Warrant of Control are usually most appropriate. For larger debts, consider Charging Orders or High Court Enforcement.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Evaluate likelihood of success</strong><br>
    Don't spend money on enforcement if the defendant has no assets, income, or ability to pay. This is known as "throwing good money after bad."
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Try multiple methods if necessary</strong><br>
    If one method fails, you can try another. For example, if Attachment of Earnings fails because the defendant is self-employed, try a Charging Order if they own property.
  </li>
</ol>

